abstract = {Ethical attention must be paid to implementing a precision medicine (PM) approach. Although PM promises targeted benefits (and reduced risks) of therapeutic and preventive interventions, it has the potential to exacerbate health disparities, particularly if environmental contributions to ill health are neglected. Its implementation presents challenges with regard to informed consent, intrafamilial disclosure of genetic risks, and discrimination and stigmatization, particularly if a polygenic risk assessment is implemented without attention to macrolevel environmental factors. Individualizing health risks increases the risk that individuals will be blamed for their ill health. Moreover, because the knowledge base for PM is currently based on genetic/genomic studies in which people of European ancestry are vastly overrepresented, those of other ancestries will not currently benefit equally from PM. Further, the high cost of PM interventions, such as rare diseases or in precision oncology, also raises concern about access and fair distribution of PM’s potential benefits.}
